HOUSE-PRICES CHALLENGE¶

1. Introduction¶

Ask a home buyer to describe their dream house, and they probably won't begin with the height of the basement ceiling or the proximity to an east-west railroad.
But this playground competition's dataset proves that much more influences price negotiations than the number of bedrooms or a white-picket fence.

With 79 explanatory variables describing (almost) every aspect of residential homes in Ames, Iowa, this competition challenges you to predict the final price of each home.

Practice Skills:

  • Creative feature engineering
  • Advanced regression techniques like random forest and gradient boosting

2. Data Exploration¶

Data source:¶

The Ames Housing dataset was compiled by Dean De Cock for use in data science education.
The data set describing the sale of individual residential property in Ames, Iowa from 2006 to 2010. The data set contains 2930 observations and a large number of explanatory variables (23 nominal, 23 ordinal, 14 discrete, and 20 continuous) involved in assessing home values.

A little to understand - Real Estate and Ames:¶

After examining the feature of apartment sales sites, it can be infer that the important features for the customer / buyer of an apartment:¶

  • Size in square feet
  • Number of bedrooms
  • number of bathrooms
  • and of course the address of the property.
    • Everyone knows that the most important thing when buying an apartment is the location! (Better location - more expensive price).

Then specify the properties:¶

  • Whether there is a pool or not
  • If the yard is designed
  • If there is a fireplace

After research on apartment pricing the hedonic method of pricing has repeatedly come up so I will detail it briefly:

Hedonic Method:¶

The basic idea of hedonic price modeling is that neighborhood-specific and unit-specific characteristics help determine house prices.
We will characterize the important variables for house pricing - size: the larger the house, the higher its value.
In addition, the question arises how to price square feet, and why is it different from house to house?
This leads us to the fact that pricing varies depending on location (better location better pricing)

More About Economic Value
More About Hedonic Pricing

Location- its all about the Loaction:¶

What does a good location mean?
Good location is also reflected in the ancillary services (eg good schools, etc.), accessibility to transportation (close to the train station, etc.), aesthetics and beauty (nice houses, trees in the streets, etc.).
Among other things, high socio-economic status - in order to increase the value of apartments.
Other things that are important in determining the prices of apartments - the number of rooms (especially - bedrooms, bathrooms and the condition of the kitchen), the age of the house (the year it was built) and the building materials are important.

To sum up-¶

Factors influencing: property size, location, nearby services, number of rooms, building materials, age of the building, condition of the building.

def get_sns_cmap(n, name='muted'):
    return sns.color_palette(palette=name, n_colors=n)

def multiplot3(data,features,plottype,figsize = (15,15),y=None,colorize=False):
    nrows = math.ceil(math.sqrt(len(features)-1))
    ncols = math.ceil((len(features)-1)/nrows)
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows, ncols,figsize=figsize)
    plt.subplots_adjust(top=3.2, bottom=0, left=0, right=2.5)
    colors = get_sns_cmap(len(features))
    n = 0
    for i in enumerate(features):
#         plt.subplot(nrows,ncols, i[0]+1)
        if plottype == 'regplot':
            if y == None:
                raise ValueError('y value is needed with regplot type')
            ax = sns.regplot(x=data[i[1]], y=data[y], data=data, color=colors[n], ax=axes[n//nrows, n%nrows], scatter_kws={"s": 40})
            ax.set_title(label=f'{i[1]} by {y}', fontsize=10)
            
        elif plottype == 'histplot': 
            ax = sns.histplot(data = data,x = data[i[1]],stat = 'density',ax=axes[n//nrows, n%nrows],color=colors[n], kde=True)
            skewness = data[i[1]].skew()
            axes[n//nrows, n%nrows].legend(["Skew : {:.2f}".format(skewness)])
        elif plottype == 'countplot':
            g = sns.countplot(data = data,x = data[i[1]], y = y, ax=axes[n//nrows, n%nrows],color = colors[n])
            g = plt.setp(g.get_xticklabels(), rotation=45)
        elif plottype == 'scatterplot':
            sns.scatterplot(data = data,x = data[i[1]], y = y, ax=axes[n//nrows, n%nrows],color = colors[n])
        n+=1
    for i in range(len(features)-1, nrows*ncols):
        fig.delaxes(axes.flatten()[i])
    # fig.show()
    display(fig)

4. Feature Engineering:¶

I will rely on the preliminary knowledge research and the attached description file-

  • 'TotalBath' -You can see that there is no finite number of baths and in the ad this feature appears at the top of the page so I will add this feature to our data.

def addTotalBath(df):
#     df_bath = df[['BsmtFullBath','BsmtHalfBath','FullBath','HalfBath']]
    df_bath = df.copy()
    df_bath['BsmtHalfBath'].replace(1, 0.5,inplace=True)
    df_bath['HalfBath'].replace(1, 0.5,inplace=True)
#     df_bath.head()
#     df_bath['TotalBath'] = df_bath['BsmtFullBath'] + df_bath['BsmtHalfBath']+ df_bath['FullBath']+ df_bath['HalfBath']
    df['TotalBath'] =  round(df_bath['BsmtFullBath'] + df_bath['BsmtHalfBath']+ df_bath['FullBath']+ df_bath['HalfBath'])
    
def addLocation(df):
    df_location = df.copy()
    df_location['ExterQual'].replace({'Po': 1, 'Fa': 2, 'TA': 3, 'Gd': 4, 'Ex': 5},inplace=True)
    df_location['ExterCond'].replace({'Po': 1, 'Fa': 2, 'TA': 3, 'Gd': 4, 'Ex': 5},inplace=True)
    df_location['Functional'].replace({'Sal': 1, 'Sev': 2, 'Maj2': 3, 'Maj1': 4, 'Mod': 5, 'Min2': 6, 'Min1': 7, 'Typ': 8},inplace=True)
    df['Location'] =((df_location['OverallQual']/df_location['OverallQual'].mean())
                    + (df_location['OverallCond']/df_location['OverallCond'].mean())
                    +(df_location['ExterQual']/df_location['ExterQual'].mean())
                    +(df_location['ExterCond']/df_location['ExterCond'].mean())+
                    (df_location['Functional']/df_location['Functional'].mean()))

5.1 Nan values¶

You can see a lot of missing values in several columns (almost all the examples are missing), but since I read the attached description file carefully and examined the data, not every value that is indicated is missing - is really missing.
For example in the alley feature - indicate Nan when there is no access to the alley.
In the Pool feature - indicate Nan when there is no pool and so on ..
Therefore before we fill in the missing values we will convert the specified values as blanks (and in practice give us information)
In fact in all the category features - when a value is marked as Nan it means that the apartment lacks this feature (for example in all the columns of the basement - NA means no basement)

In [8]:
def showNanCols(df):
    na_cols = [i for i in df.columns if df[i].isnull().any()]
    sumNan = df.isnull().sum()
    print(f'Columns that have empty values are:\n{na_cols}\nTotal empty values in the table = {sumNan.sum()}\n')
    return na_cols
# count empty values in each column
def count_empty_values_in_each_column(df: pd.DataFrame):
    print('empty values')
    print('------------\n')
    for col in df.columns:
        if df[col].isna().sum()!=0:
            print(f"{df[col].dtype} : {col}: {df[col].isna().sum()}")
        
def fill_na_random_pick_column_distribution(df, column_name):
    if column_name == "LotFrontage":
        df[column_name] = df.groupby("Neighborhood")["LotFrontage"].transform(lambda x: x.fillna(x.median()))
    else:
        df_not_null = df[~df[column_name].isnull()]
        df_null = df[df[column_name].isnull()]
#     options = np.random.choice(df_not_null[column_name])
        df[column_name] = df[column_name].apply(lambda x: np.random.choice(df_not_null[column_name]) if pd.isnull(x) else x)
    
def fill_na_values(df,min_sum_absencese = 30):
    #min_sum_absencese - The minimum set of empty category values in the table that constitute information
    # feature that dont have None as value and categorial mean absence of information
    for col in df.columns:
        if df_train[col].dtype == 'object':
            if df[col].isna().sum() > min_sum_absencese:
                df[col] = df[col].fillna("None")
            else:
                fill_na_random_pick_column_distribution(df,col)

    fill_num_na_values(df)
    return df
def fill_num_na_values(df):
    #Non-Object type
    fill_bsmt_na_vals(df)
    fill_garage_na_vals(df)
    for col in df.columns:
        if df_train[col].dtype != 'object':
            fill_na_random_pick_column_distribution(df,col)
    
def fill_bsmt_na_vals(dataset):
    dataset.loc[dataset["BsmtCond"] == "No","BsmtUnfSF"] = 0
    dataset.loc[dataset["BsmtFinType1"] == "No","BsmtFinSF1"] = 0
    dataset.loc[dataset["BsmtFinType2"] == "No","BsmtFinSF2"] = 0
    dataset.loc[dataset["BsmtQual"] == "No","TotalBsmtSF"] = 0
    dataset.loc[dataset["BsmtCond"] == "No","BsmtHalfBath"] = 0
    dataset.loc[dataset["BsmtCond"] == "No","BsmtFullBath"] = 0
    
def fill_garage_na_vals(dataset):
    dataset.loc[dataset["GarageType"] == "No","GarageCars"] = 0
    dataset.loc[dataset["GarageType"] == "No","GarageArea"] = 0
    dataset.loc[dataset["GarageType"] == "No","GarageYrBlt"] = dataset["YearBuilt"][dataset["GarageType"]=="No"]

Caution there are imposters!
As can be seen from the data - 37 numeric features and 43 categorical features (which we will need to handle carefully because coding may explode the number of columns),
But, according to the attached description file there are a number of features that are actually categorical - meaning their value is not numeric (Imposters!).
These are the following features-

  • MSSubClass - identifies the type of apartment involved in the sale (1-story, 2-story, home syle etc. You can read about the meaning of the parameters in the 2-data exploration section).
  • MoSold - Month Sold (MM)
  • YrSold: Year Sold (YYYY)

note: After trying to change 'MSSubClass' to a category, a problem was discovered - there is a unique value in the test group (150) that does not exist in the training group and therefore since the encoding chosen for MSSubClass was of the ordinal type - we chose to leave it numeric

# Function to get MAE
def get_mae(X_train, t_train, X_valid, t_valid):
    model_pipe = pipeline.make_pipeline(preprocessing.MinMaxScaler(), linear_model.SGDRegressor(random_state=1))
    model_pipe.fit(X_train, t_train)
        
    y_valid = model_pipe.predict(X_valid) # Getting predictions

    # base_model = LinearRegression()
    # base_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    # base_preds = base_model.predict(X_valid)
    return mean_absolute_error(t_valid,y_valid)

def get_num_cat_cols(data):
    categorical_cols = [col for col in data.columns if data[col].dtypes not in ["float64", "int64"]]
    numerical_cols =  [col for col in data if col not in categorical_cols]
    return numerical_cols,categorical_cols
    
def get_low_high_card_cols(data):
    numerical_cols,categorical_cols = get_num_cat_cols(data)
    # We first need to divide categorical features in low and high cardinality columns
    low_card_cols = [col for col in categorical_cols if len(data[col].unique()) < 9]
    high_card_cols = [col for col in categorical_cols if col not in low_card_cols]
    return high_card_cols,low_card_cols

def mix_encode(high_card_cols,low_card_cols,X,t = None,OH_encoder = None,ord_encoder = None,mode = 't'):
# Then, we proceed with one-hot-encoding as before, but only encoding low cardinality columns
    if OH_encoder is None:
        OH_encoder = OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore', sparse=False)
    mix_X = oh_encode(low_card_cols,X,OH_encoder,t,mode)
    if ord_encoder is None:
        ord_encoder = OrdinalEncoder(handle_unknown ='use_encoded_value',unknown_value = 150)
    if mode == 't':
        mix_X[high_card_cols] = ord_encoder.fit_transform(mix_X[high_card_cols])
    else:
        mix_X[high_card_cols] = ord_encoder.transform(mix_X[high_card_cols])
    return mix_X

def oh_encode(cat_cols,data,OH_encoder,target = None,mode = 't'):
    
    # We'll first try using one-hot-encoding exclusively
    OH_cols = None
    if mode == 't':
        OH_cols = pd.DataFrame(OH_encoder.fit_transform(data[cat_cols]))
    else:
        OH_cols = pd.DataFrame(OH_encoder.transform(data[cat_cols]))
    # Putting back index
    OH_cols.index = data.index
    # Replacing categorical columns with one-hot-encoded values
    num_X_train = data.drop(cat_cols, axis=1)
    OH_data = pd.concat([num_X_train, OH_cols], axis=1)
    return OH_data
    
def choose_encoder(X_train, X_valid,y_train,y_valid):
    cols_num,cat_features = get_num_cat_cols(X_train)
    ordinal_cols,nominal_cols = get_low_high_card_cols(X_train)

    # To keep thing simple, we drop categorical columns
    base_X_train = X_train.drop(cat_features, axis=1)
    base_X_valid = X_valid.drop(cat_features, axis=1)
    
    # Then, we define the model
    base_mae = get_mae(base_X_train, y_train, base_X_valid, y_valid)
    # We can now create a Dataframe to start storing different MAE scores.
    # This will let us keep track of our progress. 
    mae_scores =pd.DataFrame( columns=["Step","Error"])
    mae_scores.loc[0] = ["baseline model", base_mae]  
                             
   
    # mae_scores = pd.DataFrame({"Step": ["baseline model"],"Error": [base_mae]})
    
    OH_encoder = OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore', sparse=False)
    OH_X_train = oh_encode(cat_features,X_train,OH_encoder,y_train)
    OH_X_val = oh_encode(cat_features,X_valid,OH_encoder,y_valid,mode= 'v')
    OH_X_val.columns = OH_X_val.columns.astype(str)
    OH_X_train.columns = OH_X_train.columns.astype(str)
    mae_scores.loc[1] = ["OH encoding", get_mae(OH_X_train, y_train, OH_X_val, y_valid)]      
        
    OH_encoder2 = OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore', sparse=False)
    ord_encoder = OrdinalEncoder()
    MIX_X_train = mix_encode(ordinal_cols,nominal_cols,X_train,y_train,OH_encoder,ord_encoder)
    MIX_X_val = mix_encode( ordinal_cols,nominal_cols,X_valid,y_valid,OH_encoder,ord_encoder,mode= 'v')
    MIX_X_train.columns = MIX_X_train.columns.astype(str)
    MIX_X_val.columns = MIX_X_val.columns.astype(str)
    mae_scores.loc[2] = ["mixed encoding", get_mae(MIX_X_train, y_train, MIX_X_val, y_valid)]
    
    show_graph_acc(mae_scores)
    display(mae_scores)

Standard Scalar:¶

StandardScaler removes the mean and scales the data to unit variance. The scaling shrinks the range of the feature values.However, the outliers have an influence when computing the empirical mean and standard deviation.

Min-Max Scaler:¶

MinMaxScaler rescales the data set such that all feature values are in the range [0, 1]. MinMaxScaler are very sensitive to the presence of outliers.

Robust Scaler:¶

the centering and scaling statistics of RobustScaler is based on percentiles and are therefore not influenced by a few number of very large marginal outliers.

Numerical Data Scaling Methods

Compare the effect of different scalers on data with outliers
According to the above and according to the visibility of the graphs, I will select: Min-Max Scaler
This is because in linear regression I do not want to predict negative values for apartment prices.

7. Training-Time:¶

7.1 CV-cross validation:¶

We can use CV (Cross-Validation) instead of breaking the data to train-validation splits.
When we use CV, we have better predictions of the test results.
It is similar to splitting the data, but we make sure that our split won't affect our result (we try a few possible splits).
We can use 2 CV:

  1. KFold
  2. LPO (Leave P out)

We will use KFold when we want speed.
We will use LPO when we want to be more precise and better predict the test score.
More About

In [45]:
# calculate score and loss from cv (KFold or LPO) and display graphs
def get_cv_score_and_loss(X, t, model, transformer=None, k=None, p=None, show_score_loss_graphs=False, use_pbar=True):
    '''
    method that gets: data and model and 
    returns: R2 score and MSE loss
    '''
    scores_losses_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=['fold_id', 'split', 'score', 'loss'])
    X.columns = X.columns.astype(str)
    if k is not None:
        cv = model_selection.KFold(n_splits=k, shuffle=True, random_state=1)
        length = cv.n_splits
    elif p is not None:
        cv = model_selection.LeavePOut(p)
        length = cv.get_n_splits(X)
    else:
        raise ValueError('you need to specify k or p in order for the cv to work')

    if use_pbar:
        pbar = tqdm(desc='Computing Models', total=length)

    for i, (train_ids, val_ids) in enumerate(cv.split(X)):
        X_train = X.loc[train_ids+1] # Create train X and t
        t_train = t.loc[train_ids+1]
        
        X_val = X.loc[val_ids+1] # Create valid X and t
        t_val = t.loc[val_ids+1]

        model.fit(X_train, t_train) # Fitting on the model

        y_train = model.predict(X_train) # Getting predictions
        y_val = model.predict(X_val)
        
        
        scores_losses_df.loc[len(scores_losses_df)] = [i, 'train', model.score(X_train, t_train), sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(t_train, y_train))]
        scores_losses_df.loc[len(scores_losses_df)] = [i, 'val', model.score(X_val, t_val), sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(t_val, y_val))]

        if use_pbar:
            pbar.update()

    if use_pbar:
        pbar.close()

    val_scores_losses_df = scores_losses_df[scores_losses_df['split']=='val']
    train_scores_losses_df = scores_losses_df[scores_losses_df['split']=='train']

    mean_val_score = val_scores_losses_df['score'].mean()
    mean_val_loss = val_scores_losses_df['loss'].mean()
    mean_train_score = train_scores_losses_df['score'].mean()
    mean_train_loss = train_scores_losses_df['loss'].mean()

    if show_score_loss_graphs:
        fig = px.line(scores_losses_df, x='fold_id', y='score', color='split', title=f'Mean Val Score: {mean_val_score:.2f}, Mean Train Score: {mean_train_score:.2f}')
        fig.show()
        fig = px.line(scores_losses_df, x='fold_id', y='loss', color='split', title=f'Mean Val Loss: {mean_val_loss:.2f}, Mean Train Loss: {mean_train_loss:.2f}')
        fig.show()

    return mean_val_score, mean_val_loss, mean_train_score, mean_train_loss

7.2 Feature Selection:¶

We want to choose the best features for our house dataset.
There is 3 methods of Feature Selection:

  1. Forward Feature Selection
  2. Backward Feature Selection
  3. Hybrid Feature Selection

In Forward Feature Selection we start from zero features and add features until we reach the number of maximum features or until we reach the best score.
In Backward Feature Selection we start from the full feature set and remove features until we reach the number of minimum features or until we reach the best score.
In Hybrid Feature Selection, we start from zero features and add/remove features until we reach the best score.

I'll use Scikit-learn RFE that is based on the Backward Feature Selection.
I'll specify the target number of features to find and the selector will stop when it will reach this number of features.

def show_degree_graphs_cv_train(X, t, model, k=None, p=None, max_degree=10):
    numerical_cols = X.select_dtypes(include=['int64', 'float64']).columns
    categorical_cols = X.select_dtypes(include=['object', 'bool']).columns
    
    val_train_score_loss_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=['degree', 'split', 'score', 'loss'])
    for i in tqdm(range(1, max_degree), desc='Poly Degree'):
        ct_enc_std_poly = ColumnTransformer([
            ("encoding", OneHotEncoder(sparse=False, handle_unknown='ignore'), categorical_cols),
            ("standard_poly", make_pipeline(PolynomialFeatures(degree=i), MinMaxScaler()), numerical_cols)])
        model_pipe = make_pipeline(ct_enc_std_poly, model)
        val_score, val_loss, train_score, train_loss = get_cv_score_and_loss(X, t, model_pipe, transformer=ct, k=k, p=p, show_score_loss_graphs=False, use_pbar=False)
        val_train_score_loss_df.loc[len(val_train_score_loss_df)] = [i, 'train', train_score, train_loss]
        val_train_score_loss_df.loc[len(val_train_score_loss_df)] = [i, 'cv', val_score, val_loss]

    fig = px.line(val_train_score_loss_df, x='degree', y='score', color='split')
    fig.show()
    fig = px.line(val_train_score_loss_df, x='degree', y='loss', color='split')
    fig.show()

7.4 Hyper-Parameters:¶

Choosing the correct hyperparameters for machine learning or deep learning models is one of the best ways to extract the last juice out of your models.

  • what is hyper-parameters?
    • These are the parameters that cannot be estimated by the model from the given data. These parameters are used to estimate the model parameters. For example, the learning rate in deep neural networks.
  • What is hyperparameter tuning ?
    • process of determining the right combination of hyperparameters that allows the model to maximize model performance.
  • How do I choose hyper-parameters?
    1. Manual hyperparameter tuning: In this method, different combinations of hyperparameters are set (and experimented with) manually.
    2. Automated hyperparameter tuning: In this method, optimal hyperparameters are found using an algorithm that automates and optimizes the process.
  • The Hyper-Parameters I'll try to change: learning_rate
    • note: if I'll choose regularization method - I'll try to find the best penalty (count as hyper-parameter).

More About Hyper-Parameters

def best_lr(x,t,num_iter = 1000):
    scores = pd.DataFrame(columns=['lr', "val_score", "val_loss", "train_score", "train_loss"])
    lr = 0.0001
    for i in range(num_iter):
        selector = SGDRegressor(eta0=lr, learning_rate="constant",random_state=1 ).fit(x, t)
        mean_val_score, mean_val_loss, mean_train_score, mean_train_loss = get_cv_score_and_loss(x, t, selector, k=10, show_score_loss_graphs=False, use_pbar=False)
        # The process converges 
        if mean_val_loss < 0: 
            break
        #add row to our scores df
        scores.loc[len(scores)] = [lr, mean_val_score, mean_val_loss, mean_train_score, mean_train_loss]
        lr += 0.0001
    print(f'finish')
    #PLOTTING
    fig = go.Figure()
    fig.update_xaxes(title_text="Learning Rate")
    fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(x=scores["lr"], y=scores["val_score"]))
    fig.update_yaxes(title_text="CV score")
    fig.show()
    #extract max-value score to choose best learning rate
    max_score_val = scores["val_score"].max()
    row_best = scores[scores["val_score"] == max_score_val] 
    chosen_lr = row_best["lr"].to_numpy()[0]
    return chosen_lr, max_score_val

#preprocessing
categorical_cols = X_final_train.select_dtypes(include=['object', 'bool']).columns
numerical_cols = X_final_train.select_dtypes(include=['int64', 'float64']).columns
ct_final = ColumnTransformer([
    ("encoding", OneHotEncoder(sparse=False, handle_unknown='ignore'), categorical_cols),
    ("standard", make_pipeline(PolynomialFeatures(degree=2), MinMaxScaler()), numerical_cols)])
#create the model
model_pipe = make_pipeline(ct_final, SGDRegressor(penalty=rs_model.best_params_["penalty"], random_state=1, alpha=rs_model.best_params_["alpha"], eta0=chosen_lr, learning_rate="constant"))
model_pipe.fit(X_final_train,t)
#train the model
y_train_final = model_pipe.predict(X_final_train)
#error calculate
rmse = metrics.mean_squared_error(t, y_train_final, squared=False)
print(f"Final rmse = {rmse}")

Work Summary:¶

  • I started by researching the topic and gaining prior knowledge, by researching apartment sale ads in Ames Iowa I got direction on which features to look at and which not.
  • I then added features based on the prior knowledge I gained.

  • The description file was read carefully and contributed greatly to the understanding of the task.

  • Then I prepared the data - I filled in null values, compared the coding forms and chose the form that gave me the lowest error.

  • I researched in what way to normalize the data and the best scaler selected was minmax.

  • EDA performed.

  • I examined which CV to use and found that for k = 5 best results were found for validation groups. (5-fold).
  • I performed Backward Feature Selection using RFECV
  • I calculated the polynomial degree that yields the best result (found to be a magnitude 2)
  • I adjusted the hyper parameters and calculated the best learning rate for the SGD estimator, then with the help of RandomizedSearchCV the best method for performing L-regulation was discovered, as well as the alpha hyper parameter.

  • Finally model building and submission!
